\v 9 \add вүҲSo\add* \add @Ahab\add* told BenВҰ169435-Hadad's messengers, вҖңTell my masterВҰ169437 the kingВҰ169438 that \add вүҲeverything he demanded the firstВҰ169446 time\add*, I'llВҰ169447 do, \add вүҲbutВҰ169431 I can'tВҰ169450 agree to this new demand\add*.вҖқ
\p \add вүҲSo\add* \add *they\add* returned \add to Ben-Hadad\add* \add вүҲwithВҰ169446 that response\add*
\v 10 and Ben-Hadad sentВҰ169458 another message, вҖң\add вүҲThe godsВҰ169468 can do whatever theyВҰ169470 like to me and more if I leave enough dust inВҰ169481 ShomronВҰ169475 for all my prisoners to have a handfulВҰ169476 each\add*.вҖқ\f + \fr 20:10 \ft Most translations interpret вҖҳall the people at my feetвҖҷ to be Ben-Hadad's (large) army (which appears to go back at least to the Vulgate вҖҳsequiturвҖҷ), but we've TENTATIVELY interpreted it as his (future) prisoners/slaves.\f*
\p
\v 11 Yisrael'sВҰ169486 kingВҰ169484 replied, вҖңTell \add Ben-Hadad\add* \add вүҲthat someone who's heading to battle shouldn'tВҰ169489 boastВҰ169491 like someone relaxing after his victory\add*.вҖқ
\p
\v 12 \add @Ben-HadadВҰ169497\add* \add вүҲreceived that messageВҰ169499 while\add* he was inВҰ169505 the huts drinkingВҰ169502 withВҰ169505 the \add other\add* kingsВҰ169504, andВҰ169495 he \add immediately\add* \add вүҲordered his men to get into positionВҰ169511 so they got ready to attack\add* the cityВҰ169514.
